				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Higher (wind passes through)</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Appearance (Both Sides)</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Finished/unfinished</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Identical on both sides</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Material Cost</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Lower (fewer boards)</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Higher (50% more boards)</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Neighbor Relations</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">One side less attractive</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Equal appearance both sides</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>

	<h2>Privacy Considerations</h2>

	<h3>Solid Privacy Fence</h3>
	<p>As the name suggests, solid privacy fences offer complete visual screening. No one can see through the fence at any angle. This is ideal for:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Pool areas requiring privacy screening</li>
		<li>Properties adjacent to busy streets or sidewalks</li>
		<li>Hot tub or spa areas</li>
		<li>Yards backing to commercial properties</li>
		<li>Maximum security concerns</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Shadow Box Fence</h3>
	<p>Shadow box fences provide excellent privacy when viewed straight-on, but allow limited visibility at sharp angles. The overlap typically blocks 85-95% of views. This works well when:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>You want privacy but not a "fortress" feeling</li>
		<li>Neighbors are friendly and some visibility is acceptable</li>
		<li>The fence separates larger properties</li>
		<li>You prefer a lighter, more open aesthetic</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Wind Resistance: Critical for Stockton</h2>
	<p>Stockton's Delta breeze brings regular wind, making wind resistance a significant consideration:</p>

	<h3>Solid Privacy Fence Wind Challenges</h3>
	<p>Solid fences act as sails, catching wind and transferring force to posts and footings. In Stockton's wind events:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Posts experience maximum stress</li>
		<li>Fence sections can blow over in severe storms</li>
		<li>Gates may not close properly when wind-loaded</li>
		<li>Requires deeper posts and more concrete for stability</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Shadow Box Wind Advantages</h3>
	<p>The gaps in shadow box fencing allow wind to pass through, dramatically reducing stress:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Reduces wind load by 10-15%</li>
		<li>Less likely to blow over in storms</li>
		<li>Posts and footings experience less stress</li>
		<li>Better long-term stability</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Recommendation:</strong> For Stockton properties in exposed locations or areas prone to Delta breeze, shadow box fencing offers meaningful wind resistance advantages.</p>

	<h2>Airflow and Comfort</h2>

	<h3>Summer Cooling Benefits</h3>
	<p>Stockton summers regularly exceed 100°F. Airflow through your yard affects comfort:</p>

	<p><strong>Solid Privacy Fence:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Blocks cooling breezes</li>
		<li>Can create stagnant, hot air pockets</li>
		<li>May increase perceived temperature in yard</li>
		<li>Plants may suffer from lack of air circulation</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Shadow Box Fence:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Allows cooling air movement</li>
		<li>Reduces heat buildup</li>
		<li>Better for plants and gardens</li>
		<li>More comfortable outdoor living</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Moisture and Fence Longevity</h3>
	<p>Airflow also affects fence lifespan:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Better air circulation reduces moisture retention</li>
		<li>Fence dries faster after irrigation or rain</li>
		<li>Less fungal growth and rot development</li>
		<li>Potentially longer fence lifespan</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Aesthetics and Neighbor Relations</h2>

	<h3>The "Good Side" Problem</h3>
	<p>Traditional solid privacy fences have a "good side" (flat boards) and a "bad side" (exposed rails and posts). This creates a common dilemma:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Which neighbor gets the good side?</li>
		<li>Does the owner face their own bad side?</li>
		<li>Potential for neighbor friction</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Shadow Box: The True "Good Neighbor" Fence</h3>
	<p>Shadow box fencing looks identical from both sides—both neighbors see alternating boards. Benefits include:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>No awkward "which side faces out" decisions</li>
		<li>Both properties enjoy attractive fence appearance</li>
		<li>Promotes good neighbor relationships</li>
		<li>Often preferred by HOAs for this reason</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Cost Analysis</h2>

	<h3>Material Costs</h3>
	<p>Shadow box fencing requires approximately 50% more lumber than solid privacy fencing:</p>

