				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$2,700</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Posts and Rails</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$600</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$600</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Hardware</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$200</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$300</td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Estimated Material Total</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$2,600</td>
				<td style="padding: 12px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">~$3,600</td>
			</tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>

	<h3>Labor Costs</h3>
	<p>Shadow box fencing also requires more labor:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>More boards to cut and install</li>
		<li>Alternating pattern requires precision</li>
		<li>Typically 20-30% more labor time</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Total Installed Cost Comparison</h3>
	<p>For a typical 200 linear foot fence in Stockton:</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Solid Privacy:</strong> $5,000-$8,000 installed</li>
		<li><strong>Shadow Box:</strong> $7,000-$11,000 installed</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Long-Term Value Consideration</h3>
	<p>While shadow box costs more upfront, consider:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Better wind resistance may mean longer lifespan</li>
		<li>Good neighbor appearance benefits both properties</li>
		<li>Potentially better resale appeal</li>
		<li>May be required by HOA anyway</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>HOA and Code Considerations</h2>

	<h3>HOA Preferences</h3>
	<p>Many Stockton HOAs specifically require or prefer shadow box fencing because:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Uniform appearance from all viewing angles</li>
		<li>No unsightly "back side" visible to neighbors</li>
		<li>Maintains neighborhood aesthetic standards</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Building Codes</h3>
	<p>Both fence styles typically comply with Stockton building codes, but verify:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Maximum height restrictions (usually 6' in backyard)</li>
		<li>Setback requirements from property lines</li>
		<li>Material restrictions in your area</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Maintenance Comparison</h2>

	<h3>Staining and Sealing</h3>
	<p><strong>Solid Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>One side is flat and easy to stain</li>
		<li>Back side is more difficult due to rails</li>
		<li>Less surface area overall</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Shadow Box:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>More surface area (50% more boards)</li>
		<li>Both sides accessible and similar</li>
		<li>Gaps allow better penetration of stain</li>
		<li>More stain/sealer required</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Repair Considerations</h3>
	<p><strong>Solid Privacy:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Single damaged board relatively easy to replace</li>
		<li>Must match board width exactly</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Shadow Box:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Replacing boards requires working on both sides</li>
		<li>Pattern must be maintained</li>
		<li>May be slightly more complex repairs</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Alternative Options</h2>

	<h3>Board-on-Board Solid</h3>
	<p>For those wanting the aesthetics of shadow box with more privacy, consider board-on-board with tighter spacing:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Boards overlap more significantly (1-2 inches)</li>
		<li>Blocks more visibility while allowing some airflow</li>
		<li>Uses even more material than standard shadow box</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Solid Privacy with Cap and Trim</h3>
	<p>Upgrade a solid privacy fence appearance with:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Decorative post caps</li>
		<li>Top rail or cap board</li>
		<li>Trim pieces on the "bad" side</li>
		<li>Creates more finished appearance</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Making Your Decision</h2>

	<h3>Choose Solid Privacy If:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>☐ Maximum privacy is your top priority</li>
		<li>☐ You have a pool or spa requiring complete screening</li>
		<li>☐ Budget is limited and you need to minimize material costs</li>
		<li>☐ Your property is sheltered from wind</li>
		<li>☐ Neighbor relations aren't a concern (commercial neighbor, etc.)</li>
		<li>☐ HOA allows solid fencing</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Choose Shadow Box If:</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>☐ You want the fence to look good from both sides</li>
		<li>☐ Wind resistance is important for your location</li>
		<li>☐ Airflow and cooling matter in hot Stockton summers</li>
		<li>☐ You want a lighter, more open aesthetic</li>
		<li>☐ Your HOA requires or prefers this style</li>
		<li>☐ Neighbor relationships are important to maintain</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Conclusion</h2>
	<p>Both solid privacy and shadow box fences serve Stockton homeowners well—the right choice depends on your specific priorities. If absolute privacy and lower cost are paramount, solid privacy makes sense. If wind resistance, airflow, and neighbor-friendly aesthetics matter more, shadow box is worth the additional investment.</p>

	<p>Consider your property's exposure to wind, your relationships with neighbors, HOA requirements, and how you use your outdoor space. Many homeowners find the shadow box style's benefits outweigh its higher cost, while others prefer the simplicity and complete privacy of solid fencing.</p>

	<p>Want to see examples of both styles or get personalized recommendations? Contact us for a free consultation and quote for your Stockton fencing project.</p>

